# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: big-step-semantics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] In mathematical logic, a **judgment** (or **judgement**) or **assertion** is a statement or enunciation in a metalanguage.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] For example, typical judgments in first-order logic would be *that a string is a well-formed formula*, or *that a proposition is true*.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] Similarly, a judgment may assert the occurrence of a free variable in an expression of the object language, or the provability of a proposition.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] In general, a judgment may be any inductively definable assertion in the metatheory.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] Judgments are used in formalizing deduction systems: a logical axiom expresses a judgment, premises of a rule of inference are formed as a sequence of judgments, and their conclusion is a judgment as well (thus, hypotheses and conclusions of proofs are judgments).
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] A characteristic feature of the variants of Hilbert-style deduction systems is that the *context* is not changed in any of their rules of inference, while both natural deduction and sequent calculus contain some context-changing rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] Thus, if we are interested only in the derivability of tautologies, not hypothetical judgments, then we can formalize the Hilbert-style deduction system in such a way that its rules of inference contain only judgments of a rather simple form.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] The same cannot be done with the other two deductions systems: as context is changed in some of their rules of inferences, they cannot be formalized so that hypothetical judgments could be avoided—not even if we want to use them just for proving derivability of tautologies.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] This basic diversity among the various calculi allows such difference, that the same basic thought (e.g. deduction theorem) must be proven as a metatheorem in Hilbert-style deduction system, while it can be declared explicitly as a rule of inference in natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] In type theory, some analogous notions are used as in mathematical logic (giving rise to connections between the two fields, e.g.
[src:big-step-semantics/judgment-mathematical-logic] The abstraction in the notion of *judgment* in mathematical logic can be exploited also in foundation of type theory as well.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In logic and proof theory, **natural deduction** is a kind of proof calculus in which logical reasoning is expressed by inference rules closely related to the "natural" way of reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This contrasts with Hilbert-style systems, which instead use axioms as much as possible to express the logical laws of deductive reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction grew out of a context of dissatisfaction with the axiomatizations of deductive reasoning common to the systems of Hilbert, Frege, and Russell (see, e.g., Hilbert system).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Such axiomatizations were most famously used by Russell and Whitehead in their mathematical treatise *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] His proposals led to different notations such as Fitch notation or Suppes' method, for which Lemmon gave a variant now known as Suppes–Lemmon notation.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction in its modern form was independently proposed by the German mathematician Gerhard Gentzen in 1933, in a dissertation delivered to the faculty of mathematical sciences of the University of Göttingen.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen was motivated by a desire to establish the consistency of number theory.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] He was unable to prove the main result required for the consistency result, the cut elimination theorem—the Hauptsatz—directly for natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason he introduced his alternative system, the sequent calculus, for which he proved the Hauptsatz both for classical and intuitionistic logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In a series of seminars in 1961 and 1962 Prawitz gave a comprehensive summary of natural deduction calculi, and transported much of Gentzen's work with sequent calculi into the natural deduction framework.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] His 1965 monograph *Natural deduction: a proof-theoretical study* was to become a reference work on natural deduction, and included applications for modal and second-order logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In natural deduction, a proposition is deduced from a collection of premises by applying inference rules repeatedly.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The system presented in this article is a minor variation of Gentzen's or Prawitz's formulation, but with a closer adherence to Martin-Löf's description of logical judgments and connectives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction has had a large variety of notation styles, which can make it difficult to recognize a proof for a reader not familiar with one of them.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] To help with this situation, this article has a § Notation section explaining how to read all the notation that it will actually use.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This section just explains the historical evolution of notation styles, most of which cannot be shown because there are no illustrations available under a public copyright license – the reader is pointed to the SEP and IEP for pictures.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Here is a table with the most common notational variants for logical connectives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen, who invented natural deduction, had his own notation style for arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This will be exemplified by a simple argument below.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Let's say we have a simple example argument in propositional logic, such as, "if it's raining then it's cloudly; it is raining; therefore it's cloudy".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The premises are shown above a line, called the **inference line**, separated by a **comma**, which indicates *combination* of premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The conclusion is written below the inference line.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The inference line represents *syntactic consequence*, sometimes called *deductive consequence*, which is also symbolized with ⊢.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] So the above can also be written in one line as $P\to Q,P\vdash Q$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Syntactic consequence is contrasted with *semantic consequence*, which is symbolized with ⊧.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In this case, the conclusion follows *syntactically* because natural deduction is a syntactic proof system, which assumes inference rules as primitives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen's style will be used in much of this article.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen's discharging annotations used to internalise hypothetical judgments can be avoided by representing proofs as a tree of sequents *Γ* ⊢ *A* instead of a tree of judgments that *A* (is true).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Many textbooks use Suppes–Lemmon notation, so this article will also give that – although as of now, this is only included for propositional logic, and the rest of the coverage is given only in Gentzen style.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A **proof**, laid out in accordance with the Suppes–Lemmon notation style, is a sequence of lines containing sentences, where each sentence is either an assumption, or the result of applying a rule of proof to earlier sentences in the sequence.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Each **line of proof** is made up of a **sentence of proof**, together with its **annotation**, its **assumption set**, and the current **line number**.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The assumption set lists the assumptions on which the given sentence of proof depends, which are referenced by the line numbers.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The annotation specifies which rule of proof was applied, and to which earlier lines, to yield the current sentence.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This proof will become clearer when the inference rules and their appropriate annotations are specified – see § Propositional inference rules (Suppes–Lemmon style).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This section defines the formal syntax for a propositional logic language, contrasting the common ways of doing so with a Gentzen-style way of doing so.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulae, so are $(\varphi \land \psi )$ , $(\varphi \lor \psi )$ , $(\varphi \to \psi )$ , $(\varphi \leftrightarrow \psi )$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] where $\bot$ (falsum) represents a contradiction or absolute falsehood.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Older publications, and publications that do not focus on logical systems like minimal, intuitionistic or Hilbert systems, take negation as a primitive logical connective, meaning it is assumed as a basic operation and not defined in terms of other connectives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Some authors, such as Bostock, use $\bot$ and $\top$ , and also define $\neg$ as primitives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A syntax definition can also be given using § Gentzen's tree notation, by writing well-formed formulas below the inference line and any schematic variables used by those formulas above it.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A different notational convention sees the language's syntax as a categorial grammar with the single category "formula", denoted by the symbol ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Let the propositional language ${\mathcal {L}}$ be inductively defined as $\Phi ::=p_{1},p_{2},\dots \mid \bot \mid (\Phi \to \Phi )\mid (\Phi \land \Phi )\mid (\Phi \lor \Phi )$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In this table the Greek letters $\varphi ,\psi ,\chi$ are *schemata*, which range over formulas rather than only over atomic propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The name of a rule is given to the right of its formula tree.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For instance, the first introduction rule is named $\land _{I}$ , which is short for "conjunction introduction".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] ) is added to the rules for minimal logic, the system defines intuitionistic logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] When all listed natural deduction rules are admitted, the system defines classical logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Later logicians and educators such as Patrick Suppes and E.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] While they introduced graphical changes—such as replacing indentation with vertical bars—the underlying structure of Fitch-style natural deduction remained intact.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These variations are often referred to as the Suppes–Lemmon format, though they are fundamentally based on Fitch's original notation.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The linear presentation used in Fitch- and Suppes–Lemmon-style proofs — with line numbers and vertical alignment/assumption sets — makes subproofs clearly visible.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Fitch (sparingly and cautiously) used **derived rules**.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Suppes–Lemmon went further and added derived rules to the toolbox of natural deduction rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Suppes introduced natural deduction using Gentzen-style rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] He as well defined negation as implication to falsity: $\neg P\equiv P\to \bot$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In the table below, based on Lemmon (1978) and Allen & Hand (2022), Lemmon's derived rules are highlighted.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] They can be derived from the (non-highlighted) Gentzen rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] There are nine primitive rules of proof, which are the rule *assumption*, plus four pairs of introduction and elimination rules for the binary connectives, and the rules of *double negation* and *reductio ad absurdum*, of which only one is needed.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] *Disjunctive Syllogism* can be used as an easier alternative to the proper ∨-elimination, and MTT is a commonly given rule, although it is not primitive.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Recall that an example proof was already given when introducing § Suppes–Lemmon notation.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Apply $\neg \neg _{E}$ to get $\varphi$ from $\neg \neg \varphi$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A theory is said to be consistent if falsehood is not provable (from no assumptions) and is complete if every theorem or its negation is provable using the inference rules of the logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These are statements about the entire logic, and are usually tied to some notion of a model.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] However, there are local notions of consistency and completeness that are purely syntactic checks on the inference rules, and require no appeals to models.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The first of these is local consistency, also known as local reducibility, which says that any derivation containing an introduction of a connective followed immediately by its elimination can be turned into an equivalent derivation without this detour.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] It is a check on the *strength* of elimination rules: they must not be so strong that they include knowledge not already contained in their premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Dually, local completeness says that the elimination rules are strong enough to decompose a connective into the forms suitable for its introduction rule.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These notions correspond exactly to β-reduction (beta reduction) and η-conversion (eta conversion) in the lambda calculus, using the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] By local completeness, we see that every derivation can be converted to an equivalent derivation where the principal connective is introduced.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In fact, if the entire derivation obeys this ordering of eliminations followed by introductions, then it is said to be *normal*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In a normal derivation all eliminations happen above introductions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In most logics, every derivation has an equivalent normal derivation, called a *normal form*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The existence of normal forms is generally hard to prove using natural deduction alone, though such accounts do exist in the literature, most notably by Dag Prawitz in 1961.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] It is much easier to show this indirectly by means of a cut-free sequent calculus presentation.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The logic of the earlier section is an example of a *single-sorted* logic, *i.e.*, a logic with a single kind of object: propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Many extensions of this simple framework have been proposed; in this section we will extend it with a second sort of *individuals* or *terms*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] More precisely, we will add a new category, "term", denoted ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The first two rules of formation provide a definition of a term that is effectively the same as that defined in term algebra and model theory, although the focus of those fields of study is quite different from natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The third rule of formation effectively defines an atomic formula, as in first-order logic, and again in model theory.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In these rules, the notation [*t*/*x*] *A* stands for the substitution of *t* for every (visible) instance of *x* in *A*, avoiding capture.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Although the propositional logic of earlier sections was decidable, adding the quantifiers makes the logic undecidable.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] So far, the quantified extensions are *first-order*: they distinguish propositions from the kinds of objects quantified over.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Higher-order logic takes a different approach and has only a single sort of propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A discussion of the introduction and elimination forms for higher-order logic is beyond the scope of this article.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] It is possible to be in-between first-order and higher-order logics.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For example, second-order logic has two kinds of propositions, one kind quantifying over terms, and the second kind quantifying over propositions of the first kind.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The presentation of natural deduction so far has concentrated on the nature of propositions without giving a formal definition of a *proof*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] To formalise the notion of proof, we alter the presentation of hypothetical derivations slightly.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] We label the antecedents with *proof variables* (from some countable set *V* of variables), and decorate the succedent with the actual proof.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The antecedents or *hypotheses* are separated from the succedent by means of a *turnstile* (⊢).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This modification sometimes goes under the name of *localised hypotheses*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The following diagram summarises the change.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The collection of hypotheses will be written as Γ when their exact composition is not relevant.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] To make proofs explicit, we move from the proof-less judgment "*A*" to a judgment: "π *is a proof of (A)*", which is written symbolically as "π : *A*".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Following the standard approach, proofs are specified with their own formation rules for the judgment "π *proof*".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The simplest possible proof is the use of a labelled hypothesis; in this case the evidence is the label itself.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Let us re-examine some of the connectives with explicit proofs.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For conjunction, we look at the introduction rule ∧I to discover the form of proofs of conjunction: they must be a pair of proofs of the two conjuncts.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The elimination rules ∧E1 and ∧E2 select either the left or the right conjunct; thus the proofs are a pair of projections—first (**fst**) and second (**snd**).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For implication, the introduction form localises or *binds* the hypothesis, written using a λ; this corresponds to the discharged label.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In the rule, "Γ, *u*:*A*" stands for the collection of hypotheses Γ, together with the additional hypothesis *u*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] With proofs available explicitly, one can manipulate and reason about proofs.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The key operation on proofs is the substitution of one proof for an assumption used in another proof.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This is commonly known as a *substitution theorem*, and can be proved by induction on the depth (or structure) of the second judgment.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] So far the judgment "Γ ⊢ π : *A*" has had a purely logical interpretation.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In type theory, the logical view is exchanged for a more computational view of objects.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Propositions in the logical interpretation are now viewed as *types*, and proofs as programs in the lambda calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Thus the interpretation of "π : *A*" is "*the program* π has type *A*".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The logical connectives are also given a different reading: conjunction is viewed as product (×), implication as the function arrow (→), etc.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The differences are only cosmetic, however.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Type theory has a natural deduction presentation in terms of formation, introduction and elimination rules; in fact, the reader can easily reconstruct what is known as *simple type theory* from the previous sections.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The difference between logic and type theory is primarily a shift of focus from the types (propositions) to the programs (proofs).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Type theory is chiefly interested in the convertibility or reducibility of programs.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For every type, there are canonical programs of that type which are irreducible; these are known as *canonical forms* or *values*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] If every program can be reduced to a canonical form, then the type theory is said to be *normalising* (or *weakly normalising*).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] If the canonical form is unique, then the theory is said to be *strongly normalising*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Normalisability is a rare feature of most non-trivial type theories, which is a big departure from the logical world.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] (Recall that almost every logical derivation has an equivalent normal derivation.) To sketch the reason: in type theories that admit recursive definitions, it is possible to write programs that never reduce to a value; such looping programs can generally be given any type.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] In particular, the looping program has type ⊥, although there is no logical proof of "⊥".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason, the *propositions as types; proofs as programs* paradigm only works in one direction, if at all: interpreting a type theory as a logic generally gives an inconsistent logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Like logic, type theory has many extensions and variants, including first-order and higher-order versions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] One branch, known as dependent type theory, is used in a number of computer-assisted proof systems.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Dependent type theory allows quantifiers to range over programs themselves.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These types are generalisations of the arrow and product types, respectively, as witnessed by their introduction and elimination rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Dependent type theory in full generality is very powerful: it is able to express almost any conceivable property of programs directly in the types of the program.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This generality comes at a steep price — either typechecking is undecidable (extensional type theory), or extensional reasoning is more difficult (intensional type theory).
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason, some dependent type theories do not allow quantification over arbitrary programs, but rather restrict to programs of a given decidable *index domain*, for example integers, strings, or linear programs.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Since dependent type theories allow types to depend on programs, a natural question to ask is whether it is possible for programs to depend on types, or any other combination.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] There are many kinds of answers to such questions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Various combinations of dependency and polymorphism have been considered in the literature, the most famous being the lambda cube of Henk Barendregt.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The intersection of logic and type theory is a vast and active research area.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] New logics are usually formalised in a general type theoretic setting, known as a logical framework.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Popular modern logical frameworks such as the calculus of constructions and LF are based on higher-order dependent type theory, with various trade-offs in terms of decidability and expressive power.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These logical frameworks are themselves always specified as natural deduction systems, which is a testament to the versatility of the natural deduction approach.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For simplicity, the logics presented so far have been intuitionistic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] For any proposition p, the proposition p ∨ ¬p is true.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This statement is not obviously either an introduction or an elimination; indeed, it involves two distinct connectives.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] (XM3 is merely XM2 expressed in terms of E.) This treatment of excluded middle, in addition to being objectionable from a purist's standpoint, introduces additional complications in the definition of normal forms.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] A comparatively more satisfactory treatment of classical natural deduction in terms of introduction and elimination rules alone was first proposed by Parigot in 1992 in the form of a classical lambda calculus called λμ.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This structure is essentially lifted directly from classical sequent calculi, but the innovation in λμ was to give a computational meaning to classical natural deduction proofs in terms of a callcc or a throw/catch mechanism seen in LISP and its descendants.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Another important extension was for modal and other logics that need more than just the basic judgment of truth.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] These were first described, for the alethic modal logics S4 and S5, in a natural deduction style by Prawitz in 1965, and have since accumulated a large body of related work.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] If "A" (is true) under no assumption that "B" (is true), then "A valid".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Note that the premise "*A valid*" has no defining rules; instead, the categorical definition of validity is used in its place.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This mode becomes clearer in the localised form when the hypotheses are explicit.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] We write "Ω;Γ ⊢ *A*" where Γ contains the true hypotheses as before, and Ω contains valid hypotheses.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] On the right there is just a single judgment "*A*"; validity is not needed here since "Ω ⊢ *A valid*" is by definition the same as "Ω;⋅ ⊢ *A*".
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The modal hypotheses have their own version of the hypothesis rule and substitution theorem.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] This framework of separating judgments into distinct collections of hypotheses, also known as *multi-zoned* or *polyadic* contexts, is very powerful and extensible; it has been applied for many different modal logics, and also for linear and other substructural logics, to give a few examples.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] However, relatively few systems of modal logic can be formalised directly in natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] To give proof-theoretic characterisations of these systems, extensions such as labelling or systems of deep inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] The addition of labels to formulae permits much finer control of the conditions under which rules apply, allowing the more flexible techniques of analytic tableaux to be applied, as has been done in the case of labelled deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Labels also allow the naming of worlds in Kripke semantics; Simpson (1994) presents an influential technique for converting frame conditions of modal logics in Kripke semantics into inference rules in a natural deduction formalisation of hybrid logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p01] Stouppa (2004) surveys the application of many proof theories, such as Avron and Pottinger's hypersequents and Belnap's display logic to such modal logics as S5 and B.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The sequent calculus is the chief alternative to natural deduction as a foundation of mathematical logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] In natural deduction the flow of information is bi-directional: elimination rules flow information downwards by deconstruction, and introduction rules flow information upwards by assembly.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, a natural deduction proof does not have a purely bottom-up or top-down reading, making it unsuitable for automation in proof search.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] To address this fact, Gentzen in 1935 proposed his sequent calculus, though he initially intended it as a technical device for clarifying the consistency of predicate logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Kleene, in his seminal 1952 book *Introduction to Metamathematics*, gave the first formulation of the sequent calculus in the modern style.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus all inference rules have a purely bottom-up reading.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Inference rules can apply to elements on both sides of the turnstile.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] (To differentiate from natural deduction, this article uses a double arrow ⇒ instead of the right tack ⊢ for sequents.) The introduction rules of natural deduction are viewed as *right rules* in the sequent calculus, and are structurally very similar.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The elimination rules on the other hand turn into *left rules* in the sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The proposition *A ∨ B*, which is the succedent of a premise in ∨E, turns into a hypothesis of the conclusion in the left rule ∨L.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, left rules can be seen as a sort of inverted elimination rule.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus, the left and right rules are performed in lock-step until one reaches the *initial sequent*, which corresponds to the meeting point of elimination and introduction rules in natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The correspondence between the sequent calculus and natural deduction is a pair of soundness and completeness theorems, which are both provable by means of an inductive argument.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] It is clear by these theorems that the sequent calculus does not change the notion of truth, because the same collection of propositions remain true.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, one can use the same proof objects as before in sequent calculus derivations.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] As an example, consider the conjunctions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The left rule, however, performs some additional substitutions that are not performed in the corresponding elimination rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The kinds of proofs generated in the sequent calculus are therefore rather different from those of natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The sequent calculus produces proofs in what is known as the *β-normal η-long* form, which corresponds to a canonical representation of the normal form of the natural deduction proof.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] If one attempts to describe these proofs using natural deduction itself, one obtains what is called the *intercalation calculus* (first described by John Byrnes), which can be used to formally define the notion of a *normal form* for natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] The substitution theorem of natural deduction takes the form of a structural rule or structural theorem known as *cut* in the sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] In most well behaved logics, cut is unnecessary as an inference rule, though it remains provable as a meta-theorem; the superfluousness of the cut rule is usually presented as a computational process, known as *cut elimination*.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] This has an interesting application for natural deduction; usually it is extremely tedious to prove certain properties directly in natural deduction because of an unbounded number of cases.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] For example, consider showing that a given proposition is *not* provable in natural deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] A simple inductive argument fails because of rules like ∨E or E which can introduce arbitrary propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] However, we know that the sequent calculus is complete with respect to natural deduction, so it is enough to show this unprovability in the sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Now, if cut is not available as an inference rule, then all sequent rules either introduce a connective on the right or the left, so the depth of a sequent derivation is fully bounded by the connectives in the final conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, showing unprovability is much easier, because there are only a finite number of cases to consider, and each case is composed entirely of sub-propositions of the conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] A simple instance of this is the *global consistency* theorem: "⋅ ⊢ ⊥" is not provable.
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus version, this is manifestly true because there is no rule that can have "⋅ ⇒ ⊥" as a conclusion!
[src:big-step-semantics/natural-deduction-p02] Proof theorists often prefer to work on cut-free sequent calculus formulations because of such properties.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The operational semantics for a programming language describes how a valid program is interpreted as sequences of computational steps.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] These sequences then *are* the meaning of the program.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] In the context of functional programming, the final step in a terminating sequence returns the value of the program.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Perhaps the first formal incarnation of operational semantics was the use of the lambda calculus to define the semantics of Lisp.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Abstract machines in the tradition of the SECD machine are also closely related.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The concept of operational semantics was used for the first time in defining the semantics of Algol 68.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The first use of the term "operational semantics" in its present meaning is attributed to Dana Scott (Plotkin04).
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] What follows is a quote from Scott's seminal paper on formal semantics, in which he mentions the "operational" aspects of semantics.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Gordon Plotkin introduced the structural operational semantics, Matthias Felleisen and Robert Hieb the reduction semantics, and Gilles Kahn the natural semantics.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] For a simple example, we consider part of the semantics of a simple programming language; proper illustrations are given in Plotkin81 and Hennessy90, and other textbooks.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Let $C_{1},C_{2}$ range over programs of the language, and let s range over states (e.g. functions from memory locations to values).
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Informally, the rule says that "**if** the expression E in state s reduces to value V , **then** the program $L:=E$ will update the state s with the assignment $L=V$ ".
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Informally, the first rule says that, if program $C_{1}$ in state s finishes in state $s'$ , then the program $C_{1};C_{2}$ in state s will reduce to the program $C_{2}$ in state $s'$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Such a definition allows formal analysis of the behavior of programs, permitting the study of relations between programs.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Important relations include simulation preorders and bisimulation.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] These are especially useful in the context of concurrency theory.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Thanks to its intuitive look and easy-to-follow structure, SOS has gained great popularity and has become a de facto standard in defining operational semantics.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] As a sign of success, the original report (so-called Aarhus report) on SOS (Plotkin81) has attracted more than 1000 citations according to the CiteSeer [1], making it one of the most cited technical reports in Computer Science.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Reduction semantics are given as a set of *reduction rules* that each specify a single potential reduction step.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] To get an assignment statement into such a position it is “bubbled up” through function applications and the right-hand side of assignment statements until it reaches the proper point.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Since intervening $\mathbf {let}$ expressions may declare distinct variables, the calculus also demands an extrusion rule for $\mathbf {let}$ expressions.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Most published uses of reduction semantics define such “bubble rules” with the convenience of evaluation contexts.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] where e denotes arbitrary expressions and v denotes fully-reduced values.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Each evaluation context includes exactly one hole $[\,]$ into which a term is plugged in a capturing fashion.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The shape of the context indicates with this hole where reduction may occur.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] This single reduction rule is the lift rule from Felleisen and Hieb's lambda calculus for assignment statements.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The evaluation contexts restrict this rule to certain terms, but it is freely applicable in any term, including under lambdas.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Felleisen showed that imperative extensions of this calculus satisfy these theorems.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Consequences of these theorems are that the equational theory—the symmetric-transitive-reflexive closure—is a sound reasoning principle for these languages.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] However, in practice, most applications of reduction semantics dispense with the calculus and use the standard reduction only (and the evaluator that can be derived from it).
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Reduction semantics are particularly useful given the ease by which evaluation contexts can model state or unusual control constructs (e.g., first-class continuations).
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] In addition, reduction semantics have been used to model object-oriented languages, contract systems, exceptions, futures, call-by-need, and many other language features.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] A thorough, modern treatment of reduction semantics that discusses several such applications at length is given by Matthias Felleisen, Robert Bruce Findler and Matthew Flatt in *Semantics Engineering with PLT Redex*.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Big-step structural operational semantics is also known under the names **natural semantics**, **relational semantics** and **evaluation semantics**.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Big-step operational semantics was introduced under the name *natural semantics* by Gilles Kahn when presenting Mini-ML, a pure dialect of ML.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] One can view big-step definitions as definitions of functions, or more generally of relations, interpreting each language construct in an appropriate domain.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Its intuitiveness makes it a popular choice for semantics specification in programming languages, but it has some drawbacks that make it inconvenient or impossible to use in many situations, such as languages with control-intensive features or concurrency.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] A big-step semantics describes in a divide-and-conquer manner how final evaluation results of language constructs can be obtained by combining the evaluation results of their syntactic counterparts (subexpressions, substatements, etc.).
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] There are a number of distinctions between small-step and big-step semantics that influence whether one or the other forms a more suitable basis for specifying the semantics of a programming language.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] The main disadvantage of big-step semantics is that non-terminating (diverging) computations do not have an inference tree, making it impossible to state and prove properties about such computations.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] Small-step semantics give more control over the details and order of evaluation.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] In the case of instrumented operational semantics, this allows the operational semantics to track and the semanticist to state and prove more accurate theorems about the run-time behaviour of the language.
[src:big-step-semantics/operational-semantics] These properties make small-step semantics more convenient when proving type soundness of a type system against an operational semantics.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference include rules of implication, which operate only in one direction from premises to conclusions, and rules of replacement, which state that two expressions are equivalent and can be freely swapped.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They contrast with formal fallacies—invalid argument forms involving logical errors.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Logicians construct formal systems to precisely capture and codify valid patterns of reasoning, with distinct systems using different rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, propositional logic examines how statements formed through logical operators like "not" and "if...then..." support conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] First-order logic extends propositional logic by analyzing how the internal structure of propositions, like names and predicates, influences reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Other logical systems explore inferential patterns associated with what is possible and necessary, with what people believe, and with what happened at different times.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Various formalisms are used to express logical systems.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Natural deduction systems employ many intuitive rules of inference to reflect how people naturally reason, while Hilbert systems provide minimalistic frameworks to represent foundational principles without redundancy.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are relevant to many areas, such as proofs in mathematics and automated reasoning in computer science.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Their conceptual and psychological underpinnings are studied by philosophers of logic and cognitive psychologists.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] A rule of inference is a way of drawing a conclusion from a set of premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Also called *inference rule* and *transformation rule*, it is a norm of correct inferences that can be used to guide reasoning, justify conclusions, and criticize arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As part of deductive logic, rules of inference are argument forms that preserve the truth of the premises, meaning that the conclusion is always true if the premises are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] An inference is deductively valid if it follows a correct rule of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Whether this is the case depends only on the form or syntactic structure of the premises and the conclusion, that is, the actual content or concrete meaning of the statements does not affect validity.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, *modus ponens* is a rule of inference that connects two premises of the form "if P then Q " and " P " to the conclusion " Q ".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The letters P and Q in this example and in later formulas are so-called metavariables: they stand for any simple or compound proposition.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Any argument following *modus ponens* is valid, independent of the specific meanings of P and Q , such as the argument "If it is day, then it is light.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, it is light." In addition to '*modus ponens*, there are many other rules of inference, such as *modus tollens*, disjunctive syllogism, and constructive dilemma.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] There are different formats to represent rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] A common approach is to use a new line for each premise and to separate the premises from the conclusion using a horizontal line.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Some logicians employ the therefore sign ( $\therefore$ ) either together with or instead of the horizontal line to indicate where the conclusion begins.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The sequent notation, a different approach, uses a single line in which the premises are separated by commas and connected to the conclusion with the turnstile symbol ( $\vdash$ ), as in $P\to Q,P\vdash Q$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are part of logical systems and different systems employ distinct sets of rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, universal instantiation is a rule of inference in the system of first-order logic but not in propositional logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference play a central role in proofs as explicit procedures for deriving new lines of a proof from preceding lines.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Proofs involve a series of inferential steps and often use various rules of inference to establish the theorem they intend to demonstrate.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are definitory rules—rules about which inferences are allowed.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They contrast with strategic rules, which govern the inferential steps needed to prove a certain theorem from a specific set of premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Mastering definitory rules by itself is not sufficient for effective reasoning since they provide little guidance on how to reach the intended conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As standards or procedures governing the transformation of symbolic expressions, rules of inference are similar to mathematical functions taking premises as input and producing a conclusion as output.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] According to one interpretation, rules of inference are inherent in logical operators found in statements, making the meaning and function of these operators explicit without adding any additional information.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Logicians distinguish two types of rules of inference: rules of implication and rules of replacement.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of implication, like *modus ponens*, operate only in one direction, meaning that the conclusion can be deduced from the premises, but the premises cannot be deduced from the conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of replacement, by contrast, operate in both directions, stating that two expressions are equivalent and can be freely replaced with each other.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In classical logic, for example, a proposition ( P ) is equivalent to the negation of its negation ( $\lnot \lnot P$ ).
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As a result, one can infer one from the other in either direction, making it a rule of replacement.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Other rules of replacement include De Morgan's laws as well as the commutative and associative properties of conjunction and disjunction.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] While rules of implication apply only to complete statements, rules of replacement can be applied to any part of a compound statement.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Deductive rules of inference differ from defeasible argumentation schemes, which describe patterns of reasoning that provide some support to a conclusion without guaranteeing its truth, such as the argument from authority and the argument from analogy.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] However, the term "rule of inference" is sometimes used in a looser sense to include non-deductive argumentation schemes.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Similarly, the term is occasionally interpreted broadly to include general standards of research, such as the principle that scientific experiments should be replicable.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] One of the first discussions of formal rules of inference dates to antiquity, in Aristotle's logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] His explanations of valid syllogisms were further refined in medieval and early modern philosophy.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The development of symbolic logic in the 19th century, such as George Boole's articulation of Boolean algebra, led to the formulation of many additional rules of inference belonging to classical propositional and first-order logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In the 20th and 21st centuries, logicians developed various non-classical systems of logic with alternative rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference describe the structure of arguments, which consist of premises that support a conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Premises and conclusions are statements or propositions about what is true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the assertion "The door is open." is a statement that is either true or false, while the question "Is the door open?" and the command "Open the door!" are not statements and have no truth value.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] An inference is a step of reasoning from premises to a conclusion, while an argument is the outward expression of an inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Logic is the study of correct reasoning and examines how to distinguish good from bad arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Deductive logic is the branch that investigates the strongest arguments, called deductively valid arguments, for which the conclusion cannot be false if all the premises are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] This is expressed by saying that the conclusion is a logical consequence of the premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference belong to deductive logic and describe argument forms that fulfill this requirement.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In order to precisely assess whether an argument follows a rule of inference, logicians use formal languages to express statements in a rigorous manner, similar to mathematical formulas.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They combine formal languages with rules of inference to construct formal systems—frameworks for formulating propositions and drawing conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Different formal systems may employ different formal languages or different rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The basic rules of inference within a formal system can often be expanded by introducing new rules, known as *admissible rules*.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Admissible rules do not change which arguments in a formal system are valid but can simplify proofs.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] If an admissible rule can be expressed through a combination of the system's basic rules, it is called a *derived* or *derivable rule*.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Statements that can be deduced in a formal system are called *theorems* of this formal system.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Widely used systems of logic include propositional logic, first-order logic, and modal logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference only ensure that the conclusion is true if the premises are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] An argument with false premises can still be valid, but its conclusion may be false.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, the argument "If pigs can fly, then the sky is purple.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, the sky is purple." is valid because it follows *modus ponens*, even though it contains false premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] A valid argument is called a *sound argument* if all of its premises are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are closely related to tautologies or logical truths.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In logic, a tautology is a statement that is true only because of the logical vocabulary it uses, independent of the meanings of its non-logical vocabulary.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, the statement "if the tree is green and the sky is blue then the tree is green" is true independently of the meanings of terms like *tree* and *green*, making it a tautology.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Every argument following a rule of inference can be transformed into a tautology.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] This is achieved by forming a conjunction (*and*) of all premises and connecting it through implication (*if ... then ...*) to the conclusion, thereby combining all the individual statements of the argument into a single statement.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, the valid argument "The tree is green and the sky is blue.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, the tree is green." can be transformed into the tautology "if the tree is green and the sky is blue then the tree is green".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are not the only way to demonstrate that an argument is valid.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Alternative methods include the use of truth tables, which apply to propositional logic, and truth trees, which can also be employed in first-order logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Propositional logic examines the inferential patterns of simple and compound propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] It uses letters, such as P and Q , to represent simple propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Compound propositions are formed by modifying or combining simple propositions with logical operators, such as $\lnot$ (*not*), $\land$ (*and*), $\lor$ (*or*), and $\to$ (*if ... then ...*).
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, if P stands for the statement "it is raining" and Q stands for the statement "the streets are wet", then $\lnot P$ expresses "it is not raining" and $P\to Q$ expresses "if it is raining then the streets are wet".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] These logical operators are truth-functional, meaning that the truth value of a compound proposition depends only on the truth values of the simple propositions composing it.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the compound proposition $P\land Q$ is only true if both P and Q are true; in all other cases, it is false.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Propositional logic is not concerned with the concrete meaning of propositions other than their truth values.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Key rules of inference in propositional logic are *modus ponens*, *modus tollens*, hypothetical syllogism, disjunctive syllogism, and double negation elimination.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Further rules include conjunction introduction, conjunction elimination, disjunction introduction, disjunction elimination, constructive dilemma, destructive dilemma, absorption, and De Morgan's laws.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] First-order logic also employs the logical operators from propositional logic but includes additional devices to articulate the internal structure of propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Basic propositions in first-order logic consist of a predicate, symbolized with uppercase letters like P and Q , which is applied to singular terms, symbolized with lowercase letters like a and b .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, if a stands for "Aristotle" and P stands for "is a philosopher", then the formula $P(a)$ means that "Aristotle is a philosopher".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Another innovation of first-order logic is the use of the quantifiers $\exists$ and $\forall$ , which express that a predicate applies to some or all individuals.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the formula $\exists xP(x)$ expresses that philosophers exist, while $\forall xP(x)$ expresses that everyone is a philosopher.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The rules of inference from propositional logic are also valid in first-order logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Additionally, first-order logic introduces new rules of inference that govern the role of singular terms, predicates, and quantifiers in arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Key rules of inference are universal instantiation and existential generalization.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Other rules of inference include universal generalization and existential instantiation.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Modal logics are formal systems that extend propositional logic and first-order logic with additional operators.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Alethic modal logic introduces the operator $\Diamond$ to express that something is possible and the operator $\Box$ to express that something is necessary.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, if P means that "Parvati works", then $\Diamond P$ means that "It is possible that Parvati works", while $\Box P$ means that "It is necessary that Parvati works".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] These two operators are related by a rule of replacement stating that $\Box P$ is equivalent to $\lnot \Diamond \lnot P$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In other words: if something is necessarily true then it is not possible that it is not true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Further rules of inference include the necessitation rule, which asserts that a statement is necessarily true if it is provable in a formal system without any additional premises, and the distribution axiom, which allows one to derive $\Diamond P\to \Diamond Q$ from $\Diamond (P\to Q)$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] These rules of inference belong to system K, a weak form of modal logic with only the most basic rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Many formal systems of alethic modal logic include additional rules of inference, such as system T, which allows one to deduce P from $\Box P$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Non-alethic systems of modal logic introduce operators that behave like $\Diamond$ and $\Box$ in alethic modal logic, following similar rules of inference but with different meanings.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Deontic logic is one type of non-alethic logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] It uses the operator $\mathbf {P}$ to express that an action is permitted and the operator $\mathbf {O}$ to express that an action is required, where $\mathbf {P}$ behaves similarly to $\Diamond$ and $\mathbf {O}$ behaves similarly to $\Box$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the rule of replacement in alethic modal logic, which asserts that $\Box Q$ is equivalent to $\lnot \Diamond \lnot Q$ , also applies to deontic logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As a result, one can deduce from $\mathbf {O} Q$ (e.g., Quinn has an obligation to help) that $\lnot \mathbf {P} \lnot Q$ (e.g., Quinn is not permitted not to help).
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Other systems of modal logic include temporal modal logic, which has operators for what is always or sometimes the case, as well as doxastic and epistemic modal logics, which have operators for what people believe and know.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Many other systems of logic have been proposed.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In ancient Greece, one of the earliest systems was Aristotelian logic, according to which each statement is made up of two terms, a subject and a predicate, connected by a copula.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, the statement "all humans are mortal" has the subject "all humans", the predicate "mortal", and the copula "is".
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] All rules of inference in Aristotelian logic have the form of syllogisms, which consist of two premises and a conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the *Barbara* rule of inference describes the validity of arguments of the form "All men are mortal.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, all Greeks are mortal." The Nyaya school in ancient India also explored rules of inference in the form of syllogisms, such as the argument "All things which have smoke have fire.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Second-order logic extends first-order logic by allowing quantifiers to apply to predicates in addition to singular terms.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, to express that the individuals Adam ( a ) and Bianca ( b ) share a property, one can use the formula $\exists X(X(a)\land X(b))$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Second-order logic also comes with new rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, one can infer $P(a)$ (Adam is a philosopher) from $\forall XX(a)$ (every property applies to Adam).
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Intuitionistic logic is a non-classical variant of propositional and first-order logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] It shares with them many rules of inference, such as *modus ponens*, but excludes certain rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, in classical logic, one can infer P from $\lnot \lnot P$ using the rule of double negation elimination.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] However, in intuitionistic logic, this inference is invalid.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As a result, every theorem that can be deduced in intuitionistic logic can also be deduced in classical logic, but some theorems provable in classical logic cannot be proven in intuitionistic logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] One motivation for this modification is the idea that proofs should demonstrate that an object exists or can be constructed, not merely that its nonexistence would lead to a contradiction.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Paraconsistent logics revise classical logic to allow the existence of contradictions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In logic, a contradiction happens if the same proposition is both affirmed and denied, meaning that a formal system contains both P and $\lnot P$ as theorems.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Classical logic prohibits contradictions because classical rules of inference bring with them the principle of explosion, an admissible rule of inference that makes it possible to infer Q from the premises P and $\lnot P$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Since Q is unrelated to P , any arbitrary statement can be deduced from a contradiction, making the affected systems useless for deciding what is true and false.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Paraconsistent logics solve this problem by modifying the rules of inference in such a way that the principle of explosion is not an admissible rule of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As a result, it is possible to reason about inconsistent information without deriving absurd conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Many-valued logics modify classical logic by introducing additional truth values.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In classical logic, a proposition is either true or false with nothing in between.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] In many-valued logics, some propositions are neither true nor false.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Kleene logic, for example, is a three-valued logic that introduces the additional truth value *undefined* to describe situations where information is incomplete or uncertain.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Many-valued logics have adjusted rules of inference to accommodate the additional truth values.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, the classical rule of replacement stating that $P\to Q$ is equivalent to $\lnot P\lor Q$ is invalid in many three-valued systems.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Some many-valued logics take the form of probability logics, which make it possible to reason from uncertain information to probabilistic conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Various formalisms or proof systems have been suggested as distinct ways of codifying reasoning and demonstrating the validity of arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Unlike different systems of logic, these formalisms do not impact what can be proven; they only influence how proofs are formulated.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Influential frameworks include natural deduction systems, Hilbert systems, and sequent calculi.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Natural deduction systems aim to reflect how people naturally reason by introducing many intuitive rules of inference to make logical derivations more accessible.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They break complex arguments into simple steps, often using subproofs based on temporary premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The rules of inference in natural deduction target specific logical operators, governing how an operator can be added with introduction rules or removed with elimination rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, the rule of conjunction introduction asserts that one can infer $P\land Q$ from the premises P and Q , thereby producing a conclusion with the conjunction operator from premises that do not contain it.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Conversely, the rule of conjunction elimination asserts that one can infer P from $P\land Q$ , thereby producing a conclusion that no longer includes the conjunction operator.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Similar rules of inference are disjunction introduction and elimination, implication introduction and elimination, negation introduction and elimination, and biconditional introduction and elimination.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] As a result, systems of natural deduction usually include many rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Hilbert systems, by contrast, aim to provide a minimal and efficient framework of logical reasoning by including as few rules of inference as possible.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Many Hilbert systems only have *modus ponens* as the sole rule of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] To ensure that all theorems can be deduced from this minimal foundation, they introduce axiom schemes.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] An axiom scheme is a template to create axioms or true statements.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] It uses metavariables—placeholders that can be replaced by specific terms or formulas to generate an infinite number of true statements.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, propositional logic can be defined with the following three axiom schemes: (1) $P\to (Q\to P)$ , (2) $(P\to (Q\to R))\to ((P\to Q)\to (P\to R))$ , and (3) $(\lnot P\to \lnot Q)\to (Q\to P)$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] To formulate proofs, logicians create new statements from axiom schemes and then apply *modus ponens* to these statements to derive conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Compared to natural deduction, this procedure tends to be less intuitive since its heavy reliance on symbolic manipulation can obscure the underlying logical reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Sequent calculi, another approach, introduce sequents as formal representations of arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Sequents are conditional assertions stating that at least one $B_{i}$ is true if all $A_{i}$ are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference operate on sequents to produce additional sequents.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Sequent calculi define two rules of inference for each logical operator: one to introduce it on the left side of a sequent and another to introduce it on the right side.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For example, through the rule for introducing the operator $\lnot$ on the left side, one can infer $\lnot R,P\vdash Q$ from $P\vdash Q,R$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The cut rule, an additional rule of inference, makes it possible to simplify sequents by removing certain propositions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] While rules of inference describe valid patterns of deductive reasoning, formal fallacies are invalid argument forms that involve logical errors.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The premises of a formal fallacy do not properly support its conclusion: the conclusion can be false even if all premises are true.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Formal fallacies often mimic the structure of valid rules of inference and can thereby mislead people into unknowingly committing them and accepting their conclusions.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The formal fallacy of affirming the consequent concludes P from the premises $P\to Q$ and Q , as in the argument "If Leo is a cat, then Leo is an animal.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, Leo is a cat." This fallacy resembles valid inferences following *modus ponens*, with the key difference that the fallacy swaps the second premise and the conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The formal fallacy of denying the antecedent concludes $\lnot Q$ from the premises $P\to Q$ and $\lnot P$ , as in the argument "If Laya saw the movie, then Laya had fun.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Therefore, Laya did not have fun." This fallacy resembles valid inferences following *modus tollens*, with the key difference that the fallacy swaps the second premise and the conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Other formal fallacies include affirming a disjunct, the existential fallacy, and the fallacy of the undistributed middle.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are relevant to many fields, especially the formal sciences, such as mathematics and computer science, where they are used to prove theorems.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Mathematical proofs often start with a set of axioms to describe the logical relationships between mathematical constructs.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] To establish theorems, mathematicians apply rules of inference to these axioms, aiming to demonstrate that the theorems are logical consequences.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They distinguish various types of proof based on the inferential strategy to arrive at a conclusion such as direct proof, proof by contradiction, and mathematical induction.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Mathematical logic, a subfield of mathematics and logic, uses mathematical methods and frameworks to study rules of inference and other logical concepts.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Computer science also relies on deductive reasoning, employing rules of inference to establish theorems and validate algorithms.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Logic programming frameworks, such as Prolog, allow developers to represent knowledge and use computation to draw inferences and solve problems.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] These frameworks often include an automated theorem prover, a program that uses rules of inference to generate or verify proofs automatically.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Expert systems utilize automated reasoning to simulate the decision-making processes of human experts in specific fields, such as medical diagnosis, and assist in complex problem-solving tasks.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They have a knowledge base to represent the facts and rules of the field and use an inference engine to extract relevant information and respond to user queries.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are central to the philosophy of logic regarding the definition of logical consequence, which describes the relation between the premises of a deductively valid argument and its conclusion.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Different theories of this concept debate its nature and the conditions under which it exists.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] According to the deductive-theoretic conception, logical consequence is defined in terms of rules of inference: a conclusion follows logically from a set of premises if it can be deduced through a series of inferential steps.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The model-theoretic conception, by contrast, focuses on how the non-logical vocabulary of statements can be interpreted.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] According to this view, logical consequence means that no counterexamples are possible: under no interpretation are the premises true and the conclusion false.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] A related topic in the epistemology of logic concerns the question of how to justify that *modus ponens* and other rules of inference are acceptable forms of correct reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Cognitive psychologists study mental processes, including logical reasoning.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They are interested in how humans use rules of inference to draw conclusions, examining the factors that influence correctness and efficiency.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] They observe, for example, that people are better at using *modus ponens* than *modus tollens*, resulting in a higher rate of successful inferences.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] A related topic focuses on biases that lead individuals to mistake formal fallacies for valid arguments.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] For instance, fallacies of the types affirming the consequent and denying the antecedent are often mistakenly accepted as valid.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] The assessment of arguments also depends on the concrete meaning of the propositions: individuals are more likely to accept a fallacy if its conclusion sounds plausible.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] Rules of inference are also relevant to the field of law for establishing the validity of one's argument or undermining the opponent's case by exposing logical fallacies.
[src:big-step-semantics/rule-of-inference] However, legal reasoning is not limited to strict deductive inferences, incorporating aspects such as legal norms and evidentiary standards that go beyond pure formal logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In mathematical logic, a **sequent** is a very general kind of conditional assertion.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent may have any number *m* of condition formulas *Ai* (called "antecedents") and any number *n* of asserted formulas *Bj* (called "succedents" or "consequents").
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent is understood to mean that if all of the antecedent conditions are true, then at least one of the consequent formulas is true.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This style of conditional assertion is almost always associated with the conceptual framework of sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Thus sequents are a generalization of simple conditional assertions, which are a generalization of unconditional assertions.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The motivation for disjunctive semantics on the right side of a sequent comes from three main benefits.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The ease and simplicity of converting such classical rules to intuitionistic rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The ability to prove completeness for predicate calculus when it is expressed in this way.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] All three of these benefits were identified in the founding paper by Gentzen (1934, p.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Not all authors have adhered to Gentzen's original meaning for the word "sequent".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] For example, Lemmon (1965) used the word "sequent" strictly for simple conditional assertions with one and only one consequent formula.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The same single-consequent definition for a sequent is given by Huth & Ryan 2004, p.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] both Γ and Σ are sequences of logical formulas, not sets.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Therefore both the number and order of occurrences of formulas are significant.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In particular, the same formula may appear twice in the same sequence.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] 107–108), uses *sets* of formulas in sequents instead of sequences of formulas.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The symbol ' $\vdash$ ' is often referred to as the "turnstile", "right tack", "tee", "assertion sign" or "assertion symbol".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] It is often read, suggestively, as "yields", "proves" or "entails".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Since every formula in the antecedent (the left side) must be true to conclude the truth of at least one formula in the succedent (the right side), adding formulas to either side results in a weaker sequent, while removing them from either side gives a stronger one.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This is one of the symmetry advantages which follows from the use of disjunctive semantics on the right hand side of the assertion symbol, whereas conjunctive semantics is adhered to on the left hand side.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In the extreme case where the list of *antecedent* formulas of a sequent is empty, the consequent is unconditional.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This differs from the simple unconditional assertion because the number of consequents is arbitrary, not necessarily a single consequent.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Thus for example, ' ⊢ *B1*, *B2* ' means that either *B1*, or *B2*, or both must be true.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] An empty antecedent formula list is equivalent to the "always true" proposition, called the "verum", denoted "⊤".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In the extreme case where the list of *consequent* formulas of a sequent is empty, the rule is still that at least one term on the right be true, which is clearly impossible.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This is signified by the 'always false' proposition, called the "falsum", denoted "⊥".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Since the consequence is false, at least one of the antecedents must be false.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Thus for example, ' *A1*, *A2* ⊢ ' means that at least one of the antecedents *A1* and *A2* must be false.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] One sees here again a symmetry because of the disjunctive semantics on the right hand side.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] If the left side is empty, then one or more right-side propositions must be true.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] If the right side is empty, then one or more of the left-side propositions must be false.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The doubly extreme case ' ⊢ ', where both the antecedent and consequent lists of formulas are empty is "not satisfiable".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In this case, the meaning of the sequent is effectively ' ⊤ ⊢ ⊥ '.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This is equivalent to the sequent ' ⊢ ⊥ ', which clearly cannot be valid.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent of the form ' ⊢ α, β ', for logical formulas α and β, means that either α is true or β is true (or both).
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] But it does not mean that either α is a tautology or β is a tautology.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] To clarify this, consider the example ' ⊢ B ∨ A, C ∨ ¬A '.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This is a valid sequent because either B ∨ A is true or C ∨ ¬A is true.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] But neither of these expressions is a tautology in isolation.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] It is the *disjunction* of these two expressions which is a tautology.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Similarly, a sequent of the form ' α, β ⊢ ', for logical formulas α and β, means that either α is false or β is false.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] But it does not mean that either α is a contradiction or β is a contradiction.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] To clarify this, consider the example ' B ∧ A, C ∧ ¬A ⊢ '.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This is a valid sequent because either B ∧ A is false or C ∧ ¬A is false.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] But neither of these expressions is a contradiction in isolation.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] It is the *conjunction* of these two expressions which is a contradiction.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Most proof systems provide ways to deduce one sequent from another.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] These inference rules are written with a list of sequents above and below a line.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This rule indicates that if everything above the line is true, so is everything under the line.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This indicates that if we can deduce that $\Gamma ,\alpha$ yields $\Sigma$ , and that $\Gamma$ yields $\alpha$ , then we can also deduce that $\Gamma$ yields $\Sigma$ .
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The assertion symbol in sequents originally meant exactly the same as the implication operator.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] But over time, its meaning has changed to signify provability within a theory rather than semantic truth in all models.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In 1934, Gentzen did not define the assertion symbol ' ⊢ ' in a sequent to signify provability.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] He defined it to mean exactly the same as the implication operator ' ⇒ '.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Using ' → ' instead of ' ⊢ ' and ' ⊃ ' instead of ' ⇒ ', he wrote: "The sequent A1, ..., Aμ → B1, ..., Bν signifies, as regards content, exactly the same as the formula (A1 & ... & Aμ) ⊃ (B1 ∨ ... ∨ Bν)".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] (Gentzen employed the right-arrow symbol between the antecedents and consequents of sequents.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In 1939, Hilbert and Bernays stated likewise that a sequent has the same meaning as the corresponding implication formula.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In 1944, Alonzo Church emphasized that Gentzen's sequent assertions did not signify provability.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Numerous publications after this time have stated that the assertion symbol in sequents does signify provability within the theory where the sequents are formulated.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Curry in 1963, Lemmon in 1965, and Huth and Ryan in 2004 all state that the sequent assertion symbol signifies provability.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] 69) states that the assertion symbol in Gentzen-system sequents, which he denotes as ' ⇒ ', is part of the object language, not the metalanguage.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent is a formalized statement of provability that is frequently used when specifying calculi for deduction.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In the sequent calculus, the name *sequent* is used for the construct, which can be regarded as a specific kind of judgment, characteristic to this deduction system.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The intuitive meaning of the sequent $\Gamma \vdash \Sigma$ is that under the assumption of Γ the conclusion of Σ is provable.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Classically, the formulae on the left of the turnstile can be interpreted conjunctively while the formulae on the right can be considered as a disjunction.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] This means that, when all formulae in Γ hold, then at least one formula in Σ also has to be true.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] If the succedent is empty, this is interpreted as falsity, i.e. $\Gamma \vdash$ means that Γ proves falsity and is thus inconsistent.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] On the other hand an empty antecedent is assumed to be true, i.e., $\vdash \Sigma$ means that Σ follows without any assumptions, i.e., it is always true (as a disjunction).
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent of this form, with Γ empty, is known as a logical assertion.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Of course, other intuitive explanations are possible, which are classically equivalent.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] For example, $\Gamma \vdash \Sigma$ can be read as asserting that it cannot be the case that every formula in Γ is true and every formula in Σ is false (this is related to the double-negation interpretations of classical intuitionistic logic, such as Glivenko's theorem).
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In any case, these intuitive readings are only pedagogical.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Since formal proofs in proof theory are purely syntactic, the meaning of (the derivation of) a sequent is only given by the properties of the calculus that provides the actual rules of inference.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Barring any contradictions in the technically precise definition above we can describe sequents in their introductory logical form. $\Gamma$ represents a set of assumptions that we begin our logical process with, for example "Socrates is a man" and "All men are mortal".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The $\Sigma$ represents a logical conclusion that follows under these premises.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] For example "Socrates is mortal" follows from a reasonable formalization of the above points and we could expect to see it on the $\Sigma$ side of the *turnstile*.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In this sense, $\vdash$ means the process of reasoning, or "therefore" in English.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The general notion of sequent introduced here can be specialized in various ways.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] A sequent is said to be an **intuitionistic sequent** if there is at most one formula in the succedent (although multi-succedent calculi for intuitionistic logic are also possible).
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] More precisely, the restriction of the general sequent calculus to single-succedent-formula sequents, *with the same inference rules* as for general sequents, constitutes an intuitionistic sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Similarly, one can obtain calculi for dual-intuitionistic logic (a type of paraconsistent logic) by requiring that sequents be singular in the antecedent.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In many cases, sequents are also assumed to consist of multisets or sets instead of sequences.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Thus one disregards the order or even the numbers of occurrences of the formulae.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] For classical propositional logic this does not yield a problem, since the conclusions that one can draw from a collection of premises do not depend on these data.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In substructural logic, however, this may become quite important.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Natural deduction systems use single-consequence conditional assertions, but they typically do not use the same sets of inference rules as Gentzen introduced in 1934.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In particular, tabular natural deduction systems, which are very convenient for practical theorem-proving in propositional calculus and predicate calculus, were applied by Suppes (1999) and Lemmon (1965) for teaching introductory logic in textbooks.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] Historically, sequents have been introduced by Gerhard Gentzen in order to specify his famous sequent calculus.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] In his German publication he used the word "Sequenz".
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] However, in English, the word "sequence" is already used as a translation to the German "Folge" and appears quite frequently in mathematics.
[src:big-step-semantics/sequent] The term "sequent" then has been created in search for an alternative translation of the German expression.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] In the logical discipline of proof theory, a **structural rule** is an inference rule of a sequent calculus that does not refer to any logical connective but instead operates on the sequents directly.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] Structural rules often mimic the intended meta-theoretic properties of the logic.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] Logics that deny one or more of the structural rules are classified as substructural logics.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] A logic without any of the above structural rules would interpret the sides of a sequent as pure sequences; with exchange, they can be considered to be multisets; and with both contraction and exchange they can be considered to be sets.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] These are not the only possible structural rules.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] A famous structural rule is known as **cut**.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] Considerable effort is spent by proof theorists in showing that cut rules are superfluous in various logics.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] More precisely, what is shown is that cut is only (in a sense) a tool for abbreviating proofs, and does not add to the theorems that can be proved.
[src:big-step-semantics/structural-rule] The successful 'removal' of cut rules, known as *cut elimination*, is directly related to the philosophy of *computation as normalization* (see Curry–Howard correspondence); it often gives a good indication of the complexity of deciding a given logic.
